bib_record.title: Excited States in P29 from the Scattering of Protons by Si28

free_txt: The detectors were 0.025 inch thick CsI(Th)
crystals on Dumont-6291 photomultiplier tubes.
The absolute cross-section scale was determined in
the following way. It was not possible to make an
absolute determination of target thickness by
weighing. Therefore the thickness of a standard
target was determined from the Rutherford cross
section of Si for protons between 1 and 2 Mev by
measuring the elastic scattering in that range at a
number of angles and energies at which the total
cross section could legitimately be assumed to be
equal to the Rutherford cross section. All target
thicknesses were determined by counting elastically
scattered protons at 3.2 Mev and 165 degrees c.m.
using 90.0 mb/steradian as the cross section. 3.2 Mev
and 165 degrees c.m. were picked because the elastic
scattering counting rate there was known to be
insensitive to fluctuations in energy and small
errors in setting the angle.
The targets were of natural silicon (92.3% of 28Si).
Both Si metal and SiO2 foils were used.
Unless explicitly stated, the resonance
energies are believed correct to within 5 keV, except
at the end of the energy scale above 4.5 MeV where the
errors may be somewhat greater but certainly do not
exceed 10 keV. The total widths are correct within 8%,
unless  explicitly stated. The values of Gammap
Gammap/Gamma2 are estimated correct to  within 30%.
